snippet.textDisplay:
We learned so much making this episode of Spectrum! What was your favorite moment of the episode?

You can also pre-order our newest goodhuman collection Surface Level from 3/11-3/18! Promo code at the end of this video :) https://humangoodla.com
In our approach to developing ideas for the first drop of 2020, we wanted to dig just a bit deeper into topics of empathy in relation to our everyday lives. This collection explores judgement and how often we try to make sense of others at a surface level. As we endlessly scroll past the faces and lives of others, we forget the complexities behind the people. Keep searching beyond the surface, stay curious + embrace empathy.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's so like. Weird to see these types of videos. I think they're really good in helping neurotypical people understand us! But, hoo. This is hard to word? Uh... The comments are! Well meaning, but. Still condescending nonetheless! If we're normal to you, good! I'm glad! Brutal honesty? We don't need your conformation, just treat us normally. Also it like. Feels generally like we're put into this "other" box regardless whenever I see these videos. Again they are REALLY good and I think they're very important for people who have never experienced (if you're a family member but don't have it yourself, you're in this box) having autism, but, unfortunately there's just always going to be that vibe.


Anyway I really do like this video regardless, it definitely helps put into perspective that all of us are different and individual and having autism is just apart of who we are and without it we'd be completely different people.


If you're someone who has it and is thinking "I wish I didn't have it, it just makes my life harder" change that to "Everyone in my life sucks if I have this mentality and if they truly care about me, they need to show it and accommodate for me, like I likely have them." If they can't handle you, then they don't deserve you.

snippet.textDisplay: The fact that Americans have to pay huge fees to get an official test and diagnosis is terrible, when I was 16 I got sent to a child psychiatrist, tested and formally diagnosed with autism, anxiety, and depression, put on fluoxetine, and had a therapy session every 1-3 months for two years. Except the $5 anti depressant prescriptions all of this was free. How are you supposed to help anyone? Even in the eyes of those who only care about money, if autistics aren't diagnosed, then they can never get help to manage their struggles and get employment aid so they can eventually have careers that work with them, and they'll largely just remain unemployed and on benefit for the rest of their lives. In no way is the American health system logical.

snippet.textDisplay: I work at a preschool with a person who has Autism, nonverbal. He has had a really hard time feeling alright but he is coming around now and we try to work with PECS alot to give him a language and it seems to have given him some peace with the few pictures he has learned so far. Anyone with autism remember anything from your early parts of life? Having done similar things? I'm asking because I need some motivation to try and be better at working with him and helping this young kid get an easier life. His parents have really high expectations on him to be super social and play like the other kids even though he is happy with his few things he does enjoy now and slowly being introduced to socializing and other things. snippet.textDisplay:
As an autistic person, I kinda wanna answer with them??
1) absolutely agree... Special sounds SO condescending to me, like “awhhh, you’re special?? Need something?” It feels like you’re getting treated like a child
2) completely agree, I’m too honest for my own good, get kinda aggressive and ignore people I don’t like, I say weird stuff to them and make them uncomfortable without knowing... not many people around me know anything about autism, so they just assume I can read body language when I can’t (doesn’t help I have anxiety... general anxiety, I think??)
3) agree...? I already knew quite a lot, and called the [name]isms, it made me annoyed that I was diagnosed late (average age for females, but it still felt really late because medical professionals aren’t taught as much about bio females with autism, since there’s not many studies on it)
4) agree, it can make me feel better sometimes, in very specific situation, but otherwise... it feels condensing sometimes
5) strongly disagree! It’s part of my personality at this point... sometimes I feel like the reason I’m pansexual and non-binary might be because my brain is wired to be as weird and abnormal as possible... it would be better objectively, it would make me generally less anxious? But that doesn’t matter much to me
6) disagree, I don’t... know many people on the spectrum... I have a few family members, but they also have other issues (my dad could have autism, ADD and other issues), I know of one other person who I actually believe has autism, and I kinda get along with them? But I don’t really connect with them much because their fixations were much different than mine, even the opposite

Joe was the most philosophical one, which (I’m guessing) a lot of people wouldn’t expect, and I’m a lil in love with the girl who said she was super good at masking (Sorry, I’m bad at remembering things~)

I love how they did their best to work in many types of autistic people, including non-verbal people ~ 🥰

snippet.textDisplay:
I have autism, but I think I mask incredibly well, and I find it very easy to make friends. Even though I was diagnosed, I sometimes feel like I don’t actually have it because I live my life like a neurotypical. I sometimes get days where it’s worse than others but sometimes I think I understand social cues better than some neurotypicals.
My twin brother has autism, and it’s more high functioning for him and he used to have really bad anger ‘issues’ and would have daily outbursts. Sometimes I think that my original diagnosis came from me copying his behaviour as a twin, because as soon as we went to separate schools I became a lot more ‘neurotypical’ and I could fit in very easily as ‘normal’.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have PDD NOS (Pervasive Developmental Delay not otherwise specified) which puts me on the Autistic Spectrum, and I would like to answer these statements


- Do I consider the term 'special' offensive? Slightly Disagree. I'm really difficult to offend, but I can see why other people on the spectrum might. It might make those people feel lesser than others, as if we can't be held to the same standards to the "not special" kids when the truth is we all have a purpose. As Joseph perfectly said: "we are all special."


- Do I have trouble making friends? Slightly Agree. Making friends used to be a huge challenge for me in Middle School and High School, especially in the cliquey and pretentious environment I was raised in. Going off to college I found it easier to make friend groups, be it with my church and clubs, but individual friends is still difficult. Now that I'm a junior I find myself feeling content with the friends I have now and try not to be too fixated on making new ones. New friends fall in place when they fall in place.


- Has being diagnosed with Autism helped me understand myself more? Strongly Agree. I can't recall an instance when I was "diagnosed" but I definitely remember my mother explaining my learning issues to me as a kid. And having autism helped me come to grips with myself and why I am the way I am.


- Does it bother me when people pity me? Agree. I had a really hard time with feeling outcasted as a kid but I'm still really grateful and privileged for the life I am living. I have a fantastic family that has gone so many extra miles to get me to where I'm at now and I feel like many things in life have actually come to me easier than other people. So I do feel annoyed when people assume that I have it worse JUST because I'm in a neurological minority, and I think it's perfectly reasonable for people of other "marginalized" identities to feel the same way, be it with race, gender, sexuality, religion, etc.


- Would I rather not have autism? Slightly Disagree. I used to tell myself that everything would be so much better if I was just normal. Like doing well in school, not feeling like a total moron, making friends, finding a girlfriend, getting invited to parties, not being alone, picking up on sarcasm, keeping my hands to myself, controlling ticks like talking to myself, picking my nose, popping pimples, etc. NONE of this would be a problem if I didn't have any mental challenges. But then I remind myself that I never asked for any of this, it was just the card I was played and there's nothing wrong with that. I don't think I would be nearly the same person if I was "normal," and I've found a lot of self worth in my diverse range of interests, like animals, fiction, making YT videos, music, and a lot of others. I'm really inclined to say I wouldn't be that way if I wasn't born with PDD.


- Do I feel connected with other people on the spectrum? Strongly Agree. Most of my friends in Middle School and High School were also special Ed students as we all found common ground on that, like hey he gets it. Now that I'm in university most of my friends are not on the spectrum, but I think that's mostly due to people with Autism and similar mental challenges preferring different schools than the one I go to.


Thanks for reading my ramble, this is definitely one of the best Spectrum videos we've had.
